oc:kn_0435f751 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When generating the final audit report" ;
    oc:directiveContent """## Executive Summary
- Overall health assessment
- Top 3-5 priority issues
- Quick wins identified

## Technical SEO Findings
- **Issue**: {what_wrong}
- **Impact**: High/Medium/Low
- **Evidence**: {how_found}
- **Fix**: {recommendation}
- **Priority**: 1-5 or H/M/L

## On-Page SEO Findings
{same format}

## Content Findings
{same format}

## Prioritized Action Plan
1. Critical fixes (blocking indexation/ranking)
2. High-impact improvements
3. Quick wins (easy, immediate benefit)
4. Long-term recommendations""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "how_found",
        "recommendation",
        "what_wrong" .

oc:kn_04edea53 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SecurityImplication ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When validating structured data presence" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Schema markup detection requires using browser tool (document.querySelectorAll for JSON-LD), Google Rich Results Test, or Screaming Frog — not web_fetch or curl." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Using the wrong detection method produces false audit findings that mislead stakeholders into believing schema is missing when it exists." .

oc:kn_174eea17 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:directiveContent "For schema detection specifically: browser tool, Google Rich Results Test (https://search.google.com/test/rich-results), or Screaming Frog must be available." .

oc:kn_368e8686 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When performing a full SEO audit" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Check for product-marketing-context.md and load if available. 2. Gather site context (type, goals, keywords, traffic baseline). 3. Determine audit scope and tool access. 4. Execute audit in priority order: Crawlability → Technical → On-Page → Content → Authority. 5. Produce report with Executive Summary, findings per category, and Prioritized Action Plan." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_60579533 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RecoveryTactic ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When user reports traffic drop after site migration" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For post-migration traffic drops, immediately check: 301 redirect mapping, canonical tags on new pages, robots.txt not blocking crawlers, XML sitemap updated, meta tags preserved, and Search Console coverage report. Recovery monitoring may take weeks." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Migration issues are time-sensitive. Redirect failures and blocked crawl paths compound quickly as Google re-crawls and drops indexed pages." .

oc:kn_6218e48e a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When auditing indexation status" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For indexation: run site:domain.com check, review canonical tags (self-referencing, HTTPS, www consistency, trailing slash), identify noindex tags on important pages, and check for redirect chains/loops and soft 404s." ;
    oc:stepOrder 3 .

oc:kn_6f0cb92d a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Prerequisite ;
    oc:directiveContent "Site URL must be known and accessible. Google Search Console access greatly improves audit depth but is not strictly required." .

oc:kn_72aaa999 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before beginning any SEO audit" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before starting audit: confirm site URL, determine scope (full site vs specific pages), establish whether user has Search Console/analytics access, and identify priority keywords and competitors." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Scope and access constraints determine which audit checks can be performed and how deep the analysis can go." .

oc:kn_80bf434a a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When checking for structured data / schema markup during any audit" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never report 'no schema found' based solely on web_fetch or curl output. These tools strip <script> tags and cannot detect JS-injected JSON-LD schema markup." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Many CMS plugins (AIOSEO, Yoast, RankMath) inject JSON-LD via client-side JavaScript. web_fetch strips script tags during conversion, producing false negative findings." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_9236b6bc a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When evaluating site speed and Core Web Vitals" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Core Web Vitals thresholds: LCP must be < 2.5s, INP < 200ms, CLS < 0.1. A 5-6s page load is well above acceptable and directly impacts rankings." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Page speed is a confirmed Google ranking factor. Core Web Vitals are part of the Page Experience signal and directly affect mobile-first indexing readiness." .

oc:kn_a669a1c7 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "At the start of every SEO audit engagement" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Check for product-marketing-context.md (.agents/ or .claude/) before asking questions. Use that context and only ask for information not already covered." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Product marketing context provides site type, business goals, keyword priorities, and competitors — avoids redundant questioning and improves audit relevance." .

oc:kn_b5c7460c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When the site type is known" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Tailor audit focus by site type: SaaS sites commonly have thin product pages and missing comparison pages; e-commerce sites have faceted navigation duplicates and thin categories; blogs suffer from keyword cannibalization and poor internal linking; local businesses need NAP consistency and location pages." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Site-type-specific issues are the most common patterns and highest-impact fixes. Generic audits miss these recurring problems." .

oc:kn_ba6a487c a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When auditing content quality" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For content quality: assess E-E-A-T signals (experience, expertise, authoritativeness, trustworthiness), content depth vs competitors, search intent satisfaction, and user engagement metrics. Check for thin content, doorway pages, and duplicate content issues." ;
    oc:stepOrder 5 .

oc:kn_cdd00d86 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When documenting any SEO finding in the audit report" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Each audit finding must include: Issue (what's wrong), Impact (High/Medium/Low), Evidence (how you found it), Fix (specific recommendation), and Priority (1-5 or H/M/L)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Structured findings enable stakeholders to triage and act on recommendations without requiring follow-up clarification." .

oc:kn_d182e824 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When auditing on-page optimization" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For on-page SEO: verify unique title tags (50-60 chars, keyword near start), meta descriptions (150-160 chars, with CTA), one H1 per page with primary keyword, keyword in first 100 words, descriptive alt text on images, and logical internal linking with descriptive anchors." ;
    oc:stepOrder 4 .

oc:kn_d8e2d5f6 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When auditing crawlability and indexation" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For crawlability checks: verify robots.txt for unintentional blocks, confirm XML sitemap exists/submitted/correct, ensure important pages within 3 clicks of homepage, and check for orphan pages." ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

oc:kn_efef629d a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When performing any SEO audit" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Always follow the audit priority order: 1) Crawlability & Indexation → 2) Technical Foundations → 3) On-Page Optimization → 4) Content Quality → 5) Authority & Links." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Issues higher in the priority stack can block downstream improvements. Fixing on-page SEO is pointless if Google cannot crawl or index the page." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

